commitResults.messageTitle: Improve the skeletal version of Duke so that it echos commands entered by the user, and exits when the user types the command bye.
Add the ability to store whatever text entered by the user and display them back to the user when requested.
Add the ability to mark tasks as done. Optionally, add the ability to change the status back to not done.
ToDos, Events, Deadlines Add support for tracking three types of tasks:
commitResults.messageBody:
ToDos: tasks without any date/time attached to it e.g., visit new theme park
Deadlines: tasks that need to be done before a specific date/time e.g., submit report by 11/10/2019 5pm
Events: tasks that start at a specific date/time and ends at a specific date/time
e.g., (a) team project meeting 2/10/2019 2-4pm (b) orientation week 4/10/2019 to 11/10/2019

commitResults.messageTitle: Add assertions to validate task data format
commitResults.messageBody:
The loadData method checks if each task line read from the file is valid
 but does not assert that the number of fields match the expected format
 for ToDo, Deadline, or Event tasks. This can lead to subtle bugs if the
 data is malformed.

Let's add assertions to confirm the data length for each task type.
Using assertions is a lightweight way to detect unexpected data formats
during development while avoiding a runtime performance impact in
production.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add assertions for task fields and refactor to switch-case
commitResults.messageBody:
The loadData method checks if each task line is valid before parsing,
but it does not assert that the type, done status, and description
fields are valid at the outset. Without assertions, invalid data might
slip through unnoticed, leading to subtle bugs.

Additionally, using multiple if-else statements to handle task types is
less readable. A switch-case structure is more straightforward and
reduces branching complexity.

Let's assert the validity of type, done, and desc right after reading
each task’s data.

Let's also replace the if-else statements with a switch-case to
simplify the code and make it easier to maintain.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add assertion for matching fields count in saveData
commitResults.messageBody:
The saveData method converts each task’s data into a pipe-separated
string but does not verify that the number of fields in the resulting
string matches the number of elements in the taskData list. This can
lead to silent data corruption if there is a mismatch.

Let's add an assertion checking that line.split(" \| ").length equals
taskData.size(). This ensures that the string representation of each
task is consistent with its internal data structure, helping detect any
discrepancies before writing to the file.

Add upcoming command for deadlines and events
commitResults.messageBody:
Fulfills the BCD change of B-Reminders.
Currently, there's no straightforward way to remind users about
approaching tasks. This makes it harder for users to prioritize based
on urgency.

A dedicated upcoming command provides a quick view of time-sensitive
tasks by sorting them from the most urgent to the least.

Let's implement the "soon" keyword, which lists all upcoming deadlines
(sorted by the 'by' field) and events (sorted by the 'from' field).
This helps users see at a glance which tasks require immediate attention
 and plan their schedules more effectively.
